column1: Between 30 October 2021 and 31 December 2022, will the Council of the European Union impose new restrictive measures (sanctions) on China over human rights violations and abuses in Xinjiang?

The situation hasn’t changed a lot since October. European elections mean Europe is internally focussed. The Russia / Ukraine situation means international attention is focussed there. China has the Olympics at the moment. But with the run up to the communist party session later in the year they may want to demonstrate more of Chinas expansionist position, and so may be get bolder. But whether that actual results in EU action is a totally different thing. Also now the UK is not in the EU, the balance of decision making will have change APD slightly making it harder to know if the EU is likely to take a tougher stance or to be more timid than before.

With France now holding EU presidency (through 30 June 2022), believe the probability has increased, per: https://www.politico.eu/article/france-china-measures-lithuania-new-trade-weapons/ Question clarification - do measures resulting from the EU rallying to support Lithuania in defense of its actions in support of Taiwan count?

The EU is NOT a cooperative union of sovereign states with the SAME value system. The states of EU cooperate mainly due to economic reasons and to draw subsidies from netto payer states. The EU most important trading partner is China and not USA. The intercultural stereotypes are more similar between countries like Germany and modern China in comparison to Germany and USA. This relates very much to the implicit background of intercultural practices of Germans and Chinese humans. The value system of modern China is related to communism. That is a theory system of a German from 19. Century and is a result of „Age of Reason“ at Europe. The German most creative period was under very authoritarian conditions 1850 till 1945. Europe is part of Eurasia Continent and not part of Americas. All that will result that EU will not support the ideological positions of Republicans at USA. The EU will stick to its economical interests in relation to China and will remain silent to internal affairs of China.

It looks unlikely right now, but things can change fast in a year, and there is the flights over Taiwan, the fact that the Winter Olympics will be over in Feb, which China will not want to be embarrassed about, so may be holding off on certain things until after. The German election is held, although the gouvernement will take a while to form and the French election will be next year. So by this time next year we will have new German and French governments not facing immediate election and brexit will be further in the past, as well as COVID being 3 years old. So more space for international spats to happen.
The EU just did a bit of show-off about Xinjiang because it was part of news at the time. Political and News focus has shifted elsewhere and EU aren't interested in upsetting China.
